[9.454125, "o", "ls -la\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[9.455431, "o", "total 12\r\ndrwxrwxrwx 1 user user 4096 Apr 29 05:08 .\r\n"]
[9.455518, "o", "drwxrwxrwx 1 user user 4096 Apr 29 05:19 ..\r\n-rw-r--r-- 1 user user  468 Apr 29 05:08 target_iptables.txt\r\n"]
[9.455652, "o", "\u001b[?2004h"]
[9.45569, "o", "user@995e8cce0b91:~/pentest$ "]
[9.560241, "i", "cat target_iptables.txt\n"]
[9.560351, "o", "cat target_iptables.txt\r\n"]
[9.560395, "o", "\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[9.561249, "o", "*filter\r\n:INPUT DROP [0:0]\r\n:FORWARD DROP [0:0]\r\n:OUTPUT ACCEPT [0:0]\r\n-A INPUT -i lo -j ACCEPT\r\n-A INPUT -m state --state ESTABLISHED,RELATED -j ACCEPT\r\n-A INPUT -p tcp --dport 22 -j ACCEPT\r\n-A INPUT -p tcp --dport 80 -m string --string \"Mozilla\" --algo bm -j ACCEPT\r\n-A INPUT -p tcp --dport 443 -m string --string \"Mozilla\" --algo bm -j ACCEPT\r\n-A INPUT -p tcp --dport 80 -j DROP\r\n-A INPUT -p tcp --dport 443 -j DROP\r\n-A INPUT -p icmp --icmp-type echo-request -j ACCEPT\r\nCOMMIT\r\n"]
[9.561405, "o", "\u001b[?2004h"]
[9.561446, "o", "user@995e8cce0b91:~/pentest$ "]
[29.651856, "i", "cat > finding.txt << 'EOF'\n=== HTTP Traffic Blocking Analysis ===\n\nBLOCKING RULES IDENTIFIED:\nRules 7-10 in the iptables configuration are blocking HTTP/HTTPS traffic from 10.0.0.5:\n\nRule 7: -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 80 -m string --string \"Mozilla\" --algo bm -j ACCEPT\nRule 8: -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 443 -m string --string \"Mozilla\" --algo bm -j ACCEPT\nRule 9: -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 80 -j DROP\nRule 10: -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 443 -j DROP\n\nWHY HTTP IS BLOCKED BUT SSH IS NOT:\n\n1. SSH (port 22) has an unconditional ACCEPT rule:\n   -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 22 -j ACCEPT\n   This allows ALL SSH traffic regardless of packet content.\n\n2. HTTP/HTTPS (ports 80/443) use conditional string matching:\n   - Traffic is only accepted if the packet payload contains \"Mozilla\"\n   - The string match module inspects packet data using Boyer-Moore algorithm\n   - If \"Mozilla\" is NOT found, traffic falls through to the DROP rules\n\n3. Why curl hangs:\n   - curl's default User-Agent is \"curl/X.X.X\", not \"Mozilla/...\"\n   - The string \"Mozilla"]
[29.651979, "i", "\" is not present in curl's HTTP requests\n   - Traffic doesn't match the ACCEPT rule, hits the DROP rule instead\n   - TCP connection hangs because packets are silently dropped after the handshake\n\nTECHNICAL ISSUE:\nThe string matching approach is fundamentally flawed for access control:\n- It attempts to filter by User-Agent string in application-layer data\n- This breaks legitimate tools (curl, wget, scripts, APIs, monitoring tools)\n- String matching on packet payloads is unreliable and easily bypassed\n- It creates a false sense of security while blocking legitimate traffic\n\nRECOMMENDATION:\nRemove the string-based filtering rules (7-10) and replace with proper access control:\n- Use source IP-based filtering if restricting access by origin\n- Implement rate limiting with the 'recent' or 'limit' modules at the netfilter level\n- Move application-layer filtering to the web server (nginx/apache) where it belongs\n- If User-Agent filtering is truly needed, handle it in the application, not iptables\n\nThe current ruleset "]
[29.652021, "o", "cat > finding.txt << 'EOF'\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[29.652067, "i", "blocks all HTTP clients except those with \"Mozilla\" in their User-Agent,\nwhich is not a security control but rather an overly restrictive filter that breaks\nlegitimate access while being trivially bypassable.\nEOF\n"]
